observationText: The T265 cell line exhibited higher transcript levels of cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitors CDKN1A (p21), CDKN2A (p16) and CDKN1C (p57) compared to normal human Schwann cells, despite having lower protein levels of p21 and p27 and hyperphosphorylated pRB, suggesting dysregulation of cell cycle control.
The T265 cell line showed upregulation of EGFR and downregulation of adenosine receptors A2A and A2B as well as the P2Y2 purinergic receptor compared to normal human Schwann cells.
The T265 cell line was identified as potentially misidentified or a duplicate of the ST88-14 cell line based on matching STR profiles and genomic characteristics.
The T265 cell line exhibited abnormally high mRNA transcript levels of CDK2 and CDK4 compared to normal human Schwann cells, indicating an abundance of available kinases that can phosphorylate pRB.
The T265 cell line showed upregulation of cyclin D1 (CCND1) protein and cyclin D3 (CCND3) mRNA compared to normal human Schwann cells.
